Class DotParameterSetter

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.ac.man.cs.mig.util.graph.layout.dotlayoutengine.dotparser.DotParameterSetter

  • public class DotParameterSetter
extends Object
    User: matthewhorridge
    The Univeristy Of Manchester
    Medical Informatics Group
    Date: May 7, 2004

    matthew.horridge@cs.man.ac.uk
    www.cs.man.ac.uk/~horridgm

    The DotParameterSetter sets the various attributes of a Graph and it's Nodes and Edges, using attribute/value String pairs (that come from a dot file).

      • setGraphAttribute

        public void setGraphAttribute(String name,
                              String value)
        Sets an attribute for the Graph.
        Parameters:
        name - The name of the attribute, for example, "bb" will set the Graph bounding box.
        value - The value of the attribute, for example, the value "10,20,300,400" might represent a bounding box located at (10, 20), with a width of 300 and height of 400.

      • setNodeAttribute

        value - The value of the attribute

      • setEdgeAttribute

        public void setEdgeAttribute(String tailNodeID,
                             String headNodeID,
                             String name,
                             String value)
        Sets the attribute for a specified Edge. The Edge is specified in terms of the Nodes that it connects.
        Parameters:
        tailNodeID - The tail Node name.
        headNodeID - The head Node name.
        name - The name of the attribute
        value - The value of the attribute

      • setEdgePath

        public void setEdgePath(Edge edge,
                        String value)
        Sets the positions of a path origin, and the ctrl points of the path.
        Parameters:
        edge - The Edge that will have it's points set.
        value - The String containing the edge start point and ctrl points.

      • parseRect

        public Rectangle parseRect(String data)
        Parses a String that describes a Rectangle
        Parameters:
        data - A String in the format "x,y,w,h"
